 10  /-!
 11  # Properties and homomorphisms of semirings and rings
 12  
 13  This file proves simple properties of semirings, rings and domains and their unit groups. It also
 14  defines homomorphisms of semirings and rings, both unbundled (e.g. `is_semiring_hom f`)
 15  and bundled (e.g. `ring_hom a β`, a.k.a. `α →+* β`). The unbundled ones are deprecated
 16  and the plan is to slowly remove them from mathlib.
 17  
 18  ## Main definitions
 19  
 20  is_semiring_hom (deprecated), is_ring_hom (deprecated), ring_hom, nonzero_comm_semiring,
 21  nonzero_comm_ring, domain
 22  
 23  ## Notations
 24  
 25  →+* for bundled ring homs (also use for semiring homs)
 26  
 27  ## Implementation notes
 28  
 29  There's a coercion from bundled homs to fun, and the canonical
 30  notation is to use the bundled hom as a function via this coercion.
 31  
 32  There is no `semiring_hom` -- the idea is that `ring_hom` is used.
 33  The constructor for a `ring_hom` between semirings needs a proof of `map_zero`, `map_one` and
 34  `map_add` as well as `map_mul`; a separate constructor `ring_hom.mk'` will construct ring homs
 35  between rings from monoid homs given only a proof that addition is preserved.
 36  
 37  
 38  Throughout the section on `ring_hom` implicit `{}` brackets are often used instead of type class `[]` brackets.
 39  This is done when the instances can be inferred because they are implicit arguments to the type `ring_hom`.
 40  When they can be inferred from the type it is faster to use this method than to use type class inference.
 41
